0.body: Hey! In this little blog I would like to share my thoughts and experience gathered during a journey to practise C++. I write C++ code at work on a regular basis but not always can we keep up with modern tools and techniques. I decided to work on some simple project and meet some neat tools that just wait to be discovered! I hope that within my words you will find inspiration and perhaps start a similar journey on your own! Kind regards and have fun. Mateusz
0.title: Let's practice some C++!

1.body: Some time ago I realized that my C++ skills have somehow rotten and decided that I will do something about it. And here we go. I decided that I will implement something simple but while doing it, I will use modern tools and methodologies (techniques, if you will) for C++. C++20 is out there but I would like to update my skills step-by-step - I will stick with C++17. I decided that the "thing" which I shall implement will be a collection of generic containers which store their elements on the stack. I will try to keep it as independent from std as possible (so that it can be used in bare-metal projects). I will thrive for keeping everything constexpr and noexcept - which I trully like. Perhaps I will make the containers compliant with std algorithms but that is an option. Since the data will be stored on stack they will not be movable. The containers I would like to implement are: Array - collection of N items - you cannot add or remove them - you can only change their values. Stack - collection of 0 to N items - you can only add onto or remove from the top of the stack. Wheel - circular buffer - collection of 0 to N items - adding N+1'th element overrides the 1'st element and so on. Queue - collection of 0 to N items - it's easy to add elements at the end and easy to remove elements at the front. Set - collection of ordered 0 to N items without duplications. Chain - double linked list - collection of 0 to N items - it's easy to insert or remove at any place but in order to find specific element it needs to be traversed. [optional] Map - collection of 0 to N key-value pairs. Huh! That's a lot of code to be written! Perhaps the task is simple but that does not mean it will be easy. There are couple of tools I would like to exploit during the process: CMake - I am a big fan of CMake but I haven't used it in a while so it's time to update my knowledge. Conan - I was super excitet about cargo package manager for Rust lang - let's see what does C++ community have to offer. GoogleTest + GoogleMock - it's about time to invest some points in auto testing skills! clang-format - yeah - I like the code to be pretty. Git - but of course! I am currently condemned to SVN and I would love to see the add/commit/push trio again! Above all of that I will try to do my best in keeping up with TDD (Test Driven Development). Although in case of simple tasks, the fingers are just screaming to go straight for the implementation, I will patiently try to think about examples (and interfaces) first. I write code in Visual Studio Code on Ubuntu. I'm a big fan of VS Code but Ubuntu is starting to annoy me (e.g. with dummy notifications that my file browser has been successfully opened - surprise!) so it might change to Arch during the process. I compile with g++ 9.3 and use cmake 3.16. That's it for now. Until next time - farewell!
1.title: What's up?

2.body:
Let's start with some basic organization of a project. We will call it "Stack Containers" - seems to be clear and simple. At first, let's prepare some directories. For directories and non-source files I like to use kebab-case notation. It's kinda easy to read. $ mkdir stack-containers
$ cd stack-containers For sure we will have some source files and some tests. I think the implementation will be header only (since the containers are going to use templates) so there is no need for a separate include folder (which I would normally add). $ mkdir source
$ mkdir test Since we are using CMake, let's add a configuration file. $ touch CMakeLists.txt
$ code CMakeLists.txt First, let's configure CMake, project name, and C++ specific information. We specify that we want to use standard C++17 and we pass some additional flags for the compiler: turn on all standard warnings (-Wall), turn on additional warnings (-Wextra), turn every warning into an error (-Werror), and also... turn on more warnings! (-pedantic) cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.16)
project("Stack Containers" CXX) set(CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD 17)
set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS "${CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS} -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic") We could probably use older version of CMake but that's the one that I've got so let's keep it. I also really don't understand why do they use variable names with CXX instead of CPP. Oh well... The header files will be kept in source folder, so let's notify CMake about where to look for them. include_directories(source) As I promised - I will follow TDD rules. Let's start with tests. CMake has a nice feature called CTest which is helpful to distinguish compiled tests from other binaries. CMake also comes with a function add_test which is not so useful on its own but with a couple of helper functions it will do the job. Let's see. function(target_output_directory binary dir) set_target_properties(${binary} PROPERTIES RUNTIME_OUTPUT_DIRECTORY ${dir})
endfunction() function(add_new_test target) add_executable(${target} ${ARGN}) target_output_directory(${target} tests) add_test(${target} tests/${target})
endfunction() The CMake function declaration is somewhat awkward. First you use function keyword, then you pass its name as argument of function function, then you pass recognizable parameters of that function. In our case we declared two helper functions: target_output_directory - which job is to change the path where the binary target will go, and add_new_test - which is more complicated. First, it adds executable target that will be build from any source files passed as additional arguments to function add_new_test. Then, with a help of previous helper function, it changes the default output path to test directory (it is not directory with test source files but rather out-of-build test directory for binaries). In the end the function marks newly created test binary as a testable entity. Huh! Now let's add our first test. include(CTest)
enable_testing()
if(BUILD_TESTING) add_new_test(array-test test/ArrayTest.cpp)
endif() We need to include CTest in order to easily turn on/off compilation of test and testing itself. BUILD_TESTING is set to true by default but we can still disable it by passing -DBUILD_TESTING=false argument to CMake. Let's add a dummy source file for our test. $ echo "int main() { return 0; }" > test/ArrayTest.cpp Now let's try to build it. Remember to always do out of source builds. You don't want to clutter your beautiful code and project layout with some compile-time garbage! $ mkdir build
$ cd build
$ cmake .. After that I received the following output. -- The CXX compiler identification is GNU 9.3.0
-- Check for working CXX compiler: /usr/bin/c++
-- Check for working CXX compiler: /usr/bin/c++ -- works
-- Detecting CXX compiler ABI info
-- Detecting CXX compiler ABI info - done
-- Detecting CXX compile features
-- Detecting CXX compile features - done
-- Configuring done
-- Generating done
-- Build files have been written to: /home/tysik/Workspace/cpp/stack-containers/build And now it's time for make! $ make
Scanning dependencies of target array-test
[ 50%] Building CXX object CMakeFiles/array-test.dir/test/ArrayTest.cpp.o
[100%] Linking CXX executable tests/array-test
[100%] Built target array-test Can we run the test? Sure we can! $ make test
Running tests...
Test project /home/tysik/Workspace/cpp/stack-containers/build Start 1: array-test
1/1 Test #1: array-test ....................... Passed 0.00 sec 100% tests passed, 0 tests failed out of 1 Total Test time (real) = 0.00 sec That's it for now. We will prepare some real test suites in a near future. Until next time - farewell!
